rs, exposing the problems in their lives often overlooked in pregnancy prevention campaigns. Some stories are tragic and painful, marked by sexual abuse, partner violence, and school failure. Others depict "girl next door" characters whose unintended pregnancies lay bare insidious gender disparities. Offering a fresh perspective on the links between teen births and social inequalities, this book demonstrates how the intersecting hierarchies of gender, race, and class shape the biographies of young mothers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aTeenage girlszUnited StatesxSocial conditions. 0aTeenage pregnancyzUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh  a21st century.  abiographical.  achildhood.  adropout rates.  aethnographers.  aethnography.  agender issues.  aincarceration.  amoral order.  amotherhood.  anew parents.  anew york city.  anonfiction.  apartner violence.  apoverty cycle.  apublic education campaigns.  arace and class issues.  aschool dropouts.  aschool failure.  asexual abuse.  asocial inequalities.  asociologists.  asociology.  ateen moms.  ateen mothers.  ateen parents.  ateen pregnancy rates.  ateen pregnancy.  atragic.  ayoung mothers.1 aBlack, Timothy, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z97831106211120 cprintz978052028341140uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095928640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520959286423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520959286/original  a978-3-11-062111-2  University of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY